Origin: surfaced in PR #255 conversation as "It's related to the changes from #249, in that it breaks my ability to launch kanban with a file I've just created, at least on Windows." Independent of #255 itself — separate bug, separate fix.

## Summary

PR #249 introduced kanban-service/src/path.rs::validate_path, which is now called from kanban-cli/src/app.rs before opening the data file. On Windows, validate_path rejects valid in-cwd paths whenever the target file actually exists, with the misleading error "Path traversal not allowed".

## Offending code (crates/kanban-service/src/path.rs, lines 22-35)

    if path.is_absolute() {
        Ok(path.canonicalize().unwrap_or_else(|_| path.to_path_buf()))
    } else {
        let resolved = cwd.join(path);
        let canonical = resolved
            .canonicalize()
            .unwrap_or_else(|_| normalize_path(&resolved));
        if !canonical.starts_with(cwd) {
            return Err(KanbanError::validation(format!(
                "Path traversal not allowed: '{}' resolves outside current directory",
                path.display()
            )));
        }
        Ok(canonical)
    }

## Root cause

std::fs::canonicalize on Windows always returns a UNC long-path: \\?\C:\Users\foo\kanban.json. This is a long-standing Rust stdlib quirk; the stdlib docs explicitly warn about it, and the `dunce` crate exists solely to strip the prefix.

std::env::current_dir() returns a non-UNC path: C:\Users\foo.

On the relative-path branch:

    cwd       = C:\Users\foo\proj
    canonical = \\?\C:\Users\foo\proj\kanban.json
    canonical.starts_with(cwd) -> false

Path::starts_with is component-based, and the UNC prefix introduces an extra \\?\ component. The traversal check rejects the path even though it resolves to a file literally inside cwd. The user sees "Path traversal not allowed: 'kanban.json' resolves outside current directory" — a false positive.

## Why only "file I just created" triggers it

canonicalize requires the target to exist. When the file does not exist yet, the unwrap_or_else fallback to normalize_path runs, which produces a non-UNC path; starts_with succeeds and the call returns OK.

So the reproduction is sensitive to whether the file was created before launch:

    kanban kanban.json     (file doesn't exist) -> works (creates new, no UNC produced)
    New-Item kanban.json
    kanban kanban.json     (file now exists)    -> "Path traversal not allowed"

The absolute-path branch (line 23) is also affected but in a different way: canonicalize succeeds, the UNC-prefixed PathBuf is returned, and the prefix leaks downstream to whichever store opens the file. Whether that breaks depends on the downstream consumer's tolerance for UNC paths; in practice many Windows APIs handle both, so this branch may be silently fine — but it is still wrong-shaped.

## Why CI did not catch it

- .github/workflows/ci.yml runs only on ubuntu-latest. No Windows job. On Linux/macOS canonicalize does not UNC-prefix, so the bug is invisible to CI.
- The unit test test_validate_path_relative_within_cwd_returns_resolved uses Path::new("some/nested/file.json") inside a fresh TempDir — the file does not exist, so the test hits the normalize_path fallback, not the canonicalize branch. Same on every OS.
- test_validate_path_absolute_passes_through uses dir.path().join("file.json") which also does not exist. Same fallback.

There is literally zero coverage of "the file exists" on the canonicalize branch.

## Suggested fixes (three options)

1. Use `dunce::canonicalize` instead of Path::canonicalize. The dunce crate is ~150 LOC, single-purpose, and returns \\?\C:\... -> C:\.... Drop-in:

       let canonical = dunce::canonicalize(&resolved).unwrap_or_else(|_| normalize_path(&resolved));

   Apply on both the absolute-path and relative-path branches. This is the conventional Rust answer for this exact bug.

2. Strip the prefix manually on Windows, no new dep:

       fn strip_unc(p: PathBuf) -> PathBuf {
           #[cfg(windows)] {
               if let Some(s) = p.to_str().and_then(|s| s.strip_prefix(r"\\?\")) {
                   return PathBuf::from(s);
               }
           }
           p
       }

   Wrap both canonicalize calls.

3. Canonicalize both sides before comparing. Canonicalize cwd too on the relative-path branch; both have UNC, starts_with works. Does not address the absolute-path branch leaking UNC downstream.

Option 1 is the cleanest and matches what the rest of the Rust ecosystem does.

