## Severity

High-ish. It is a hard "I can't open my data" failure for Windows users who pre-create their kanban file. Workaround is to delete the file and let kanban (re)create it, which only works if the file is empty.

## Problem

Every call to `mutating_op!` in `kanban-mcp/src/lib.rs` begins with
`guard.reload()`, which fully discards the in-memory cache and resets undo
history to the current on-disk state. This means `tool_undo` can only ever
undo the single operation from the **current** tool call — it cannot reach
back to undo an operation performed in a previous API call within the same
session.

## Root cause

`KanbanContext::reload()` is the only way to pick up external file changes, but
it also wipes the command log and resets `undo_cursor` to 0. Since `mutating_op!`
always reloads (defensively, to pick up any external edits), it always destroys
history.

## Proposed fix: `KanbanBackend::reload_if_changed()`

Add a method to the `KanbanBackend` trait:

```rust
/// Reload only if the backing file has changed since the last save.
/// Returns `true` if a reload was performed (history cleared),
/// `false` if the file is unchanged and history was preserved.
async fn reload_if_changed(&self) -> KanbanResult<bool> {
    Ok(false) // default: write-through backends never need a reload
}
```

### Detection strategy

`JsonDataStore` already tracks `FileMetadata` (mtime + size via
`last_known_metadata: Mutex<Option<FileMetadata>>` in `JsonFileStore`). Compare
the on-disk metadata with the last-known metadata:

```rust
async fn reload_if_changed(&self) -> KanbanResult<bool> {
    let on_disk = FileMetadata::from_file(self.file_store.path())?;
    let last = self.file_store.last_known_metadata(); // new accessor
    if Some(on_disk) != last {
        self.reload().await?;
        Ok(true)
    } else {
        Ok(false)
    }
}
```

A secondary check can compare `instance_id` from the file envelope against
`self.file_store.instance_id()` to detect writes by other processes even if
mtime resolution is coarse (e.g. FAT32, 2-second granularity).

### `mutating_op!` change

```rust
macro_rules! mutating_op {
    ($ctx:expr, $method:ident $(, $arg:expr)*) => {{
        async {
            let mut guard = $ctx.lock().await;
            guard.reload_if_changed().await.map_err(kanban_err_to_mcp)?;
            let result = guard.$method($($arg),*).map_err(kanban_err_to_mcp)?;
            guard.save().await.map_err(kanban_err_to_mcp)?;
            Ok::<_, McpError>(result)
        }
        .await
    }};
}
```

### `KanbanContext` surface

```rust
pub async fn reload_if_changed(&mut self) -> KanbanResult<bool> {
    if self.backend.reload_if_changed().await? {
        // Full reload happened — reinitialise undo state.
        self.baseline_snapshot = None;
        self.undo_cursor = 0;
        self.command_count = 0;
        self.dirty = false;
        let baseline = self.backend.snapshot()?;
        self.backend.truncate_commands_after(0)?;
        self.baseline_snapshot = Some(baseline);
        self.notify_undo_state()?;
        Ok(true)
    } else {
        Ok(false)
    }
}
```

## Motivation / user-visible impact

Without this fix, an MCP client that calls `tool_create_board` followed
immediately by `tool_undo` gets the board back — **but** if it calls
`tool_create_board` and then `tool_create_column` and then `tool_undo`, the
undo only removes the column, leaving the board. A second `tool_undo` returns
`false` (nothing to undo) because the reload at the start of `tool_create_column`
wiped the board-creation from history.

With `reload_if_changed`, history accumulates across calls as long as no
external process modifies the file between calls (the common case for a single
LLM session). This makes multi-step undo work naturally.

