## Problem

In `crates/kanban-domain/src/error.rs::DomainError::fmt_batch_resolution_failed`
the pluralization logic is implemented inline and a comment narrates what
the code does:

```rust
fn fmt_batch_resolution_failed(entity: &str, failures: &[BatchResolutionFailure]) -> String {
    // Singularize the entity noun when there's exactly one failure;
    // otherwise add a plural `s`. Keep entity capitalization for
    // consistency with `NotFoundByName` and `Ambiguous` siblings.
    let n = failures.len();
    let noun = if n == 1 {
        entity.to_string()
    } else {
        format!("{}s", entity)
    };
    ...
}
```

The comment is doing work the code should do on its own — it explains the
"what" of three trivial lines, and a future reader has to trust the comment
matches the implementation. Classic narration anti-pattern.

## Fix sketch

Pull pluralization into a self-documenting helper so the call site reads
its intent without prose:

```rust
fn pluralize(noun: &str, count: usize) -> String {
    if count == 1 {
        noun.to_string()
    } else {
        format!("{}s", noun)
    }
}

fn fmt_batch_resolution_failed(entity: &str, failures: &[BatchResolutionFailure]) -> String {
    let parts = failures
        .iter()
        .map(ToString::to_string)
        .collect::<Vec<_>>()
        .join(", ");
    format!(
        "Could not resolve {} {}: {}",
        failures.len(),
        pluralize(entity, failures.len()),
        parts
    )
}
```

The call site now reads `pluralize(entity, n)` — no comment needed.

The "keep entity capitalization for consistency with siblings" half of the
old comment is also redundant: there's no `to_lowercase()` in sight to
warn against, so a future reader has no reason to wonder. The contract
is enforced by absence.

