- Follows KAN-522 (raised in round-4 review as SO-1).
- Sibling of KAN-526 (MCP+SQLite test parity) and KAN-527 (storage version bump enforcement) — all surfaced by the same review pass.
- Not blocking anything.

## Stakeholder summary — Where, Why, How

**Where.** `crates/kanban-service/src/json_backend.rs` (JsonDataStore) and `crates/kanban-service/src/sqlite_backend.rs` (SqliteBackend). Both crates now hold an identically-shaped `last_metadata: RwLock<Option<PersistenceMetadata>>` field, an identical `persistence_metadata()` accessor, and near-identical write-on-update patterns.

**Why.** KAN-522 introduced the metadata cache twice — once in JsonDataStore for the F12 panel and once in SqliteBackend to avoid per-render DB hits. The two implementations are byte-for-byte identical on the read side and structurally identical on the write side:

```rust
// Identical in both backends:
fn persistence_metadata(&self) -> Option<PersistenceMetadata> {
    self.last_metadata.read().ok().and_then(|g| g.clone())
}

// Near-identical (only the error prefix string differs):
let mut guard = self.last_metadata.write().map_err(|_| {
    KanbanError::Internal("X_backend: last_metadata RwLock poisoned".into())
})?;
*guard = Some(...);
```

Round-4 review identified this as SO-2 ("the two impls could share a trait method"). It's not enough duplication on its own to demand a refactor today, but if a third backend ever lands (in-process server? S3? RPC?), the pattern will exist in three places, and the right shape for sharing it will be less obvious in retrospect.

The card exists to document the option so the next contributor adding a backend has a clean path, rather than discovering the duplication and either re-implementing it for a third time or doing a larger refactor under deadline pressure.

**How.** Three options worth weighing, each is straightforward and each has different scope. The recommended one is **B** (helper struct with composition), because it preserves backend autonomy while pulling the cache shape into one place.

