## What

The stateful `SprintPicker::handle_key` in
`crates/kanban-tui/src/components/sprint_picker.rs:47` only matches
`KeyCode::Up`/`KeyCode::Down`. The vim-style `j`/`k` aliases used
everywhere else in the TUI are silently dropped.

```rust
// crates/kanban-tui/src/components/sprint_picker.rs:56-69 (current)
match key_code {
    KeyCode::Down => { /* select next */ true }
    KeyCode::Up   => { /* select prev */ true }
    _ => false,
}
```

The docstring on the same function explicitly promises j/k:

```rust
// lines 44-46
/// Try to consume a navigation key. Returns true when the key moved the
/// selection (Up/Down/j/k); false when the key should fall through to
/// other handlers (typing into a text input, etc.).
```

So this is a contract violation, not an open question of intent.

## Why

KAN-557 (PR #309, commit `846e59d8`) extracted `RadioList` and the new
stateful `SprintPicker` for reuse from the existing
`sprint_assign_list` / sprint-assign popup. The extraction *lost* the
`j`/`k` half of the navigation pattern. The legacy callsite still has
the full pattern:

- **Working** — `crates/kanban-tui/src/handlers/popup_handlers.rs:241,248`
  ```rust
  KeyCode::Char('j') | KeyCode::Down => { ... next_selectable ... }
  KeyCode::Char('k') | KeyCode::Up   => { ... prev_selectable ... }
  ```
- **Broken** — `SprintPicker::handle_key` (Up/Down only).

User-visible impact: any host that delegates navigation to
`SprintPicker::handle_key` ignores `j`/`k`. The current consumer is the
in-progress Create Card sprint picker on the KAN-556 branch
(`crates/kanban-tui/src/app/dialog_input.rs:24 — create_card_sprint_picker: SprintPicker`).
Pressing `j` or `k` in that sprint section returns `false` from the
picker, so the host treats the key as text input and the cursor never
moves. The standalone "assign to sprint" popup is unaffected because it
predates the SprintPicker extraction and routes through
`handle_assign_card_to_sprint_popup` directly.

The existing unit test
`test_handle_key_down_advances_selection_and_returns_true`
(`sprint_picker.rs:178`) covers `Down` only, so the j/k drop slipped
past CI.

## How (concrete implementation)

Red → Green → Refactor.

### 1. Red — failing test pinning the contract

Add to the existing `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` in
`crates/kanban-tui/src/components/sprint_picker.rs`. Mirror the existing
Down-advances test and add a `k` mirror:

```rust
#[test]
fn test_handle_key_char_j_advances_selection_like_down() {
    let now = Utc::now();
    let board = make_board();
    let planning_a = Sprint::new(board.id, 1, None, None);
    let planning_b = Sprint::new(board.id, 2, None, None);
    let sprints = vec![planning_a, planning_b];

    let mut picker = SprintPicker::new();
    picker.reset_for_board(&sprints, &board, now);
    let before = picker.selection_index();

    let consumed = picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Char('j'), &sprints, &board, now);
    let after = picker.selection_index();

    assert!(consumed, "j should be consumed by the picker (vim alias of Down)");
    assert_ne!(before, after, "j should move selection like Down");
}

#[test]
fn test_handle_key_char_k_retreats_selection_like_up() {
    let now = Utc::now();
    let board = make_board();
    let planning_a = Sprint::new(board.id, 1, None, None);
    let planning_b = Sprint::new(board.id, 2, None, None);
    let sprints = vec![planning_a, planning_b];

    let mut picker = SprintPicker::new();
    picker.reset_for_board(&sprints, &board, now);
    // Advance once so k has somewhere to go.
    picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Down, &sprints, &board, now);
    let before = picker.selection_index();

    let consumed = picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Char('k'), &sprints, &board, now);
    let after = picker.selection_index();

    assert!(consumed, "k should be consumed by the picker (vim alias of Up)");
    assert_ne!(before, after, "k should move selection like Up");
}
```

Run `cargo test -p kanban-tui --test sprint_picker_tests` (or
`cargo test -p kanban-tui sprint_picker::tests` for inline tests) — both
new tests must fail with `consumed = false` and `after == before`.

### 2. Green — extend the match arms

```rust
// crates/kanban-tui/src/components/sprint_picker.rs:56-69
match key_code {
    KeyCode::Down | KeyCode::Char('j') => {
        if let Some(next) = next_selectable(&entries, cur) {
            self.selection.set(Some(next));
        }
        true
    }
    KeyCode::Up | KeyCode::Char('k') => {
        if let Some(prev) = prev_selectable(&entries, cur) {
            self.selection.set(Some(prev));
        }
        true
    }
    _ => false,
}
```

Both new tests now pass; the existing
`test_handle_key_other_returns_false_so_host_can_handle_it` continues
to pass (it asserts `Char('a')`, `Enter`, `Backspace` — not `j`/`k`).

### 3. Refactor — strengthen the negative test

Update
`test_handle_key_other_returns_false_so_host_can_handle_it` to also
assert that non-navigation chars like `'a'` *and* `'h'`/`'l'` (vim
horizontal motion) still return `false`. Documents the intentional
scope and guards against future "swallow all letters" drift:

```rust
assert!(!picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Char('a'), &sprints, &board, now));
assert!(!picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Char('h'), &sprints, &board, now));
assert!(!picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Char('l'), &sprints, &board, now));
assert!(!picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Enter, &sprints, &board, now));
assert!(!picker.handle_key(KeyCode::Backspace, &sprints, &board, now));
```

## Alternative solutions (considered, rejected)

### Alt A — handle j/k in the host, leave the picker stateless w.r.t. vim aliases

Have `dialog_handlers.rs::handle_create_card_dialog` rewrite
`Char('j')` → `Down` and `Char('k')` → `Up` before calling
`SprintPicker::handle_key`.

**Rejected** because:
- It pushes vim aliasing concerns onto every future host of
  `SprintPicker` (and the upcoming `CheckList<T>` per the KAN-557
  commit history mentions KAN-558).
- The picker's own docstring already commits to handling j/k.
- The legacy `handle_assign_card_to_sprint_popup` proves the convention
  is "the navigation handler accepts both" in this codebase.

### Alt B — centralise `is_nav_down(key) -> bool` / `is_nav_up(key) -> bool` helpers in `list_nav`

`crates/kanban-tui/src/components/list_nav.rs` is the existing single
source of truth for predicate-based list navigation (introduced in
KAN-557 itself). Add two trivial predicates:

```rust
pub fn is_nav_down(k: KeyCode) -> bool {
    matches!(k, KeyCode::Down | KeyCode::Char('j'))
}
pub fn is_nav_up(k: KeyCode) -> bool {
    matches!(k, KeyCode::Up | KeyCode::Char('k'))
}
```

Then `SprintPicker::handle_key`, the legacy popup handler, and any
future CheckList/RadioList host all consume the same predicate.

**Deferred, not rejected.** This is the right long-term shape — it
removes the duplicated `KeyCode::Char('j') | KeyCode::Down` pattern
which already exists at dozens of sites
(`crates/kanban-tui/src/handlers/popup_handlers.rs`, `column_handlers.rs`,
`detail_view_handlers.rs`, `filter_handlers.rs`,
`settings_handlers.rs`, `card_list_component.rs`). But it is a broader
refactor that fixes a structural smell, not the regression. **File as a
separate card** ("Extract `is_nav_up`/`is_nav_down` predicates into
`list_nav`; migrate ~15 callsites") — do this card as the minimal fix
first so the regression closes quickly.

## Out of scope

- The broader vim-alias-predicate refactor (Alt B). Separate card.
- `KeyCode::Char('h')` / `Char('l')` horizontal motion — the picker is
  a vertical list with a single column, so horizontal navigation has
  no semantics here.
- Restoring j/k to any other extracted component. None observed; this
  audit was scoped to `SprintPicker`.

## Origin

PR #309 (`846e59d8 KAN-557 refactor(tui): extract RadioList and
SprintPicker for reuse`). Surfaced while testing the in-progress
KAN-556 (create-card with optional sprint assignment) branch — the
embedded `SprintPicker` consumer of the new stateful component.

### Overview

**Where**: `kanban-tui` component layer. Multi-select (checkbox) list patterns are implemented inline and independently in at least three places: sprint filter section (`components/filter_popup.rs:43`), relationship management popup (`components/relationship_popup.rs:78`), and export board selector (`ui/dialogs/boards.rs:12`). A navigation-only primitive exists (`components/generic_list.rs:8`) but carries no rendering logic.

**Why**: Each callsite re-implements the same `[✓]`/`[ ]` rendering, cursor tracking, and toggle logic independently, making visual consistency and future behaviour changes require parallel edits across the codebase.

**How**: Build a generic `CheckList<T>` component -- parallel to the `RadioList<T>` introduced in KAN-557 -- that owns checkbox rendering, cursor navigation, and toggle/check-all semantics; then implement a `SprintFilterPicker` adapter over it to replace the inline sprint multi-select in the filter dialog. Both `RadioList<T>` and `CheckList<T>` compose a shared `ListItem<T>` type.

---

### Engineering detail

**Existing duplication to be replaced**:

`kanban-tui/src/components/filter_popup.rs:43-143` -- inline sprint checkbox list in `render_filter_sprints_section`, builds sprint lines manually with cursor prefix and `[✓]`/`[ ]` symbols, owns its own scroll:
```rust
for (idx, sprint) in board_sprints.iter().enumerate() {
    let is_selected = dialog_state.filters.selected_sprint_ids.contains(&sprint.id);
    let cursor = if section_index == 0 && dialog_state.item_selection == idx + 1 { "> " } else { "  " };
    // ... builds Line manually
}
```

`kanban-tui/src/components/relationship_popup.rs:78-127` -- inline card checkbox list in `render_relationship_card_list`, uses `[✓]`/`[ ]` with `HashSet<Uuid>` for checked state:
```rust
let checkbox = if is_checked { "[✓]" } else { "[ ]" };
```

`kanban-tui/src/ui/dialogs/boards.rs:12-59` -- inline board checkbox list in `render_export_boards_popup`, uses `[x]`/`[ ]` with `Vec<bool>`:
```rust
if dialog.board_selections.get(i).copied().unwrap_or(false) { "[x] " } else { "[ ] " }
```

`kanban-tui/src/components/generic_list.rs:8` -- `ListComponent` has `multi_selected: HashSet<usize>` and `toggle_multi_select()` but no rendering; it is navigation-only and index-based with no value type.

**Shared foundation with KAN-557**:

`RadioList<T>` (KAN-557) and `CheckList<T>` (this card) share an identical item representation. Extract it into a shared type:

```rust
// kanban-tui/src/components/list_item.rs (or top of radio_list.rs / check_list.rs)
pub struct ListItem<T> {
    pub value: T,
    pub label: Line<'static>,  // pre-rendered; colour and modifiers baked in
    pub selectable: bool,       // false for section headers / separators
}
```

`RadioList<T>` uses `ListItem<T>` with `selected: Option<usize>` (single selection).
`CheckList<T>` uses `ListItem<T>` with `checked: HashSet<usize>` + `cursor: usize` (multi-selection).

Neither inherits from the other. Composition: both hold `Vec<ListItem<T>>` and implement their own navigation and render logic.

**Layer 1 -- generic `CheckList<T>`** (new file `kanban-tui/src/components/check_list.rs`):

```rust
pub struct CheckList<T> {
    items: Vec<ListItem<T>>,
    checked: HashSet<usize>,  // indices of checked selectable items
    cursor: usize,            // current keyboard focus (selectable items only)
}

impl<T: Clone> CheckList<T> {
    pub fn new(items: Vec<ListItem<T>>, pre_checked: HashSet<usize>) -> Self { ... }

    /// Toggle the checked state of the item under the cursor.
    pub fn toggle_cursor(&mut self) { ... }

    /// Check all selectable items.
    pub fn check_all(&mut self) { ... }

    /// Uncheck all selectable items.
    pub fn clear_all(&mut self) { ... }

    pub fn cursor_next(&mut self) { /* skip non-selectable */ }
    pub fn cursor_prev(&mut self) { /* skip non-selectable */ }

    /// Values of all currently checked items.
    pub fn checked_values(&self) -> Vec<&T> { ... }

    /// Render into area. Draws [✓]/[ ] prefix; cursor row highlighted.
    /// Handles scroll and sticky section-header overlay (same as RadioList).
    pub fn render(&self, frame: &mut Frame, area: Rect) { ... }
}
```

`CheckList` knows nothing about sprints, cards, or boards. Its only domain is `ListItem<T>`.

**Layer 2 -- `SprintFilterPicker` adapter** (new file `kanban-tui/src/components/sprint_filter_picker.rs`):

```rust
