## Proposed solution

### Step 1 — Add the helper to `field_update.rs`

```rust
// crates/kanban-domain/src/field_update.rs

/// Returns the `FieldUpdate` that, when applied, reverses the effect
/// of `patch` on `current`. If `patch` made no change, the inverse
/// is `NoChange`. Otherwise the inverse restores `current`: `Set(v)`
/// if there was a value, `Clear` if there wasn't.
///
/// Used by `capture_inverse` implementations on update commands to
/// build the undo command from the pre-mutation entity state.
pub fn invert_optional<T: Clone>(
    patch: &FieldUpdate<T>,
    current: &Option<T>,
) -> FieldUpdate<T> {
    match patch {
        FieldUpdate::NoChange => FieldUpdate::NoChange,
        _ => match current {
            Some(v) => FieldUpdate::Set(v.clone()),
            None => FieldUpdate::Clear,
        },
    }
}
```

This is the only doc comment in the entire change — it's load-bearing because the function name doesn't tell you the `NoChange` branch is preserved.

### Step 2 — Migrate every offender

```rust
// Before
description: match upd.description {
    FieldUpdate::NoChange => FieldUpdate::NoChange,
    _ => match card.description {
        Some(v) => FieldUpdate::Set(v),
        None => FieldUpdate::Clear,
    },
},

// After
description: invert_optional(&upd.description, &card.description),
```

Apply to every `FieldUpdate<T>` field in `UpdateCard::capture_inverse`, `UpdateColumn::capture_inverse`, `UpdateSprint::capture_inverse`. The `Option<T>` fields (title, priority, status, position, column_id — which use `.map(|_| card.x.clone())` not `FieldUpdate`) are unaffected.

