# Section: Command trait + BackendExecutor → kanban-core

kanban-domain's `Command` enum (crates/kanban-domain/src/commands/mod.rs:23-71) exposes three inherent methods on every variant: `execute(&CommandContext)`, `capture_inverse(&dyn DataStore)`, `description()`. There is no actual `trait Command` anywhere. To let the generic `Context<B, Cmd>` (separate section) dispatch commands without knowing what `Cmd` is, define an abstract `Command<Ctx>` trait in kanban-core and a `BackendExecutor<Cmd>` bridge trait that lets the generic Context obtain a `Ctx` and `Store` from any `Backend` for each command dispatch.

## Suggested design

`crates/kanban-core/src/command.rs`:

```rust
use crate::CoreResult;

/// Generic, reversible domain command. Implemented by the consumer's
/// top-level command type (kanban: the `Command` enum; SRS: `SrsCommand`).
pub trait Command: Clone + Send + Sync + 'static {
    /// Execution context borrowed from the backend for this dispatch.
    /// GAT lets the lifetime tie to the backend reference.
    type Ctx<'a>;

    /// Read-only store for inverse capture. `?Sized` so it can be a
    /// trait object (`dyn DataStore`).
    type Store: ?Sized + 'static;

    fn execute(&self, ctx: &Self::Ctx<'_>) -> CoreResult<()>;
    fn capture_inverse(&self, store: &Self::Store) -> CoreResult<Vec<Self>>;
}

/// "Command meets Backend" bridge. The generic `Context<B, Cmd>` calls
/// these methods on its `B` to obtain a `Cmd::Ctx` and `Cmd::Store`
/// without knowing what either type is.
pub trait BackendExecutor<Cmd: Command>: Send + Sync {
    fn ctx(&self) -> Cmd::Ctx<'_>;
    fn store(&self) -> &Cmd::Store;

    /// Append a batch of executed commands to an append-only audit log.
    /// Default `Ok(())` lets consumers without an audit log opt out.
    fn append_to_audit(&self, _cmds: &[Cmd]) -> CoreResult<()> { Ok(()) }
}
```

kanban-domain side — one thin adapter `impl Command for kanban_domain::commands::Command` that delegates to the existing inherent methods:

```rust
impl Command for kanban_domain::commands::Command {
    type Ctx<'a> = CommandContext<'a>;
    type Store = dyn DataStore;
    fn execute(&self, ctx: &Self::Ctx<'_>) -> CoreResult<()> {
        Command::execute(self, ctx).map_err(CoreError::from)
    }
    fn capture_inverse(&self, store: &Self::Store) -> CoreResult<Vec<Self>> {
        Command::capture_inverse(self, store).map_err(CoreError::from)
    }
}
```

kanban-service side — `impl BackendExecutor<kanban_domain::commands::Command> for dyn KanbanBackend` in a new `command_executor.rs` module. Routes `ctx()` and `store()` through `as_data_store()`, routes `append_to_audit()` through `CommandStore::append_commands`.

## Alternatives considered

- **Single trait with `Vec<Self>` inverse (CHOSEN)**: zero allocation overhead beyond what kanban already does (Vec<Command>), round-trips through serde unchanged, exactly mirrors the current shape.
- **`type Inverse: Command<Ctx>` (typed per-command inverse)**: kanban's inverses are *heterogeneous* (DeleteBoard's inverse is a mixed vec across multiple sub-enums). Forces `type Inverse = Self;` anyway, recreating the recursion. **Rejected.**
- **`Box<dyn Command<Ctx>>` inverse**: kills the serde round-trip (audit log can't deserialize boxed dyn objects cleanly). **Rejected.**
- **Visitor pattern with `Handler<Cmd>` trait**: doubles surface area per command, breaks open/closed for enum extensions. **Rejected.**

