# Living proof: a non-kanban consumer can satisfy Context

## Motivation
The whole sprint exists so a second consumer (Korean SRS app) can reuse the framework. Prove it by adding an integration test in kanban-core that builds a tiny SRS-shaped consumer end-to-end using ONLY `kanban_core::{Backend, BackendExecutor, Command, Context}`. No kanban-domain, no kanban-persistence, no kanban-service imports.

Doubles as living documentation for the SRS team.

## Current state
None — this is a new file.

## Target shape
`crates/kanban-core/tests/srs_demo.rs`:

```rust
//! Sanity test: proves a non-kanban consumer can use `kanban_core::Context`.
//! Models a tiny SRS learning app: a `reviewed` counter with Increment/Decrement
//! commands. End-to-end execute/undo/redo, no kanban-domain imports.

use kanban_core::{Backend, BackendExecutor, Command, Context, CoreError, CoreResult};
use std::sync::{Arc, RwLock};

// ── Domain ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#[derive(Default)]
struct SrsStore { reviewed: RwLock<u32> }

// ── Commands ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
enum SrsCmd { Increment, Decrement }

impl Command for SrsCmd {
    type Ctx<'a> = &'a SrsStore;
    type Store = SrsStore;

    fn execute(&self, ctx: &Self::Ctx<'_>) -> CoreResult<()> {
        let mut g = ctx.reviewed.write().unwrap();
        match self {
            SrsCmd::Increment => *g = g.saturating_add(1),
            SrsCmd::Decrement => *g = g.saturating_sub(1),
        }
        Ok(())
    }

    fn capture_inverse(&self, _: &Self::Store) -> CoreResult<Vec<Self>> {
        Ok(vec![match self {
            SrsCmd::Increment => SrsCmd::Decrement,
            SrsCmd::Decrement => SrsCmd::Increment,
        }])
    }
}

// ── Backend ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
struct SrsBackend { store: SrsStore }

#[async_trait::async_trait]
impl Backend for SrsBackend {
    type Snapshot = u32;
    fn snapshot(&self) -> CoreResult<u32> {
        Ok(*self.store.reviewed.read().unwrap())
    }
    fn apply_snapshot(&self, s: u32) -> CoreResult<()> {
        *self.store.reviewed.write().unwrap() = s;
        Ok(())
    }
}

impl BackendExecutor<SrsCmd> for SrsBackend {
    fn ctx(&self) -> &SrsStore { &self.store }
    fn store(&self) -> &SrsStore { &self.store }
}

// ── Tests ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#[tokio::test]
async fn srs_consumer_executes_undoes_redoes() {
    let backend = Arc::new(SrsBackend { store: SrsStore::default() });
    let mut ctx: Context<SrsBackend, SrsCmd> = Context::new(backend.clone());

    ctx.execute(vec![SrsCmd::Increment, SrsCmd::Increment]).unwrap();
    assert_eq!(*backend.store.reviewed.read().unwrap(), 2);
    assert_eq!(ctx.undo_depth(), 1);

    assert!(ctx.undo().unwrap());
    assert_eq!(*backend.store.reviewed.read().unwrap(), 0);
    assert_eq!(ctx.redo_depth(), 1);

    assert!(ctx.redo().unwrap());
    assert_eq!(*backend.store.reviewed.read().unwrap(), 2);
    assert_eq!(ctx.undo_depth(), 1);
}

#[test]
fn srs_consumer_can_replace_backend() {
    let backend1 = Arc::new(SrsBackend { store: SrsStore::default() });
    let mut ctx: Context<SrsBackend, SrsCmd> = Context::new(backend1);
    ctx.mark_dirty();
    assert!(ctx.is_dirty());

    let backend2 = Arc::new(SrsBackend { store: SrsStore::default() });
    ctx.replace_backend(backend2);
    assert!(!ctx.is_dirty(), "dirty should clear");
}
```

